<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
When we collected the animal (habitus 
<figureCitation box="[686,794,1112,1137]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1046,1068]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1024]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1024]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Habitus. A Adapantus excavatus n. sp., B Conocephalus iris, var. guineensis, C Brachyamytta bombomensis n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600954/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 5 A</figureCitation>
) on 
<collectingCountry box="[858,954,1112,1137]" name="Sao Tome and Principe" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Príncipe</collectingCountry>
, we expected to have found 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Krauss" baseAuthorityYear="1890" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transmarinus">Adapantus transmarinus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
known for this island from literature (see above). However, it differs distinctly from this species and has to be described as a new species which may even not be the sister species to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Krauss" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[1053,1202,1186,1209]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transmarinus">
<emphasis box="[1053,1202,1186,1209]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">transmarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1220,1245]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Differs from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1891" box="[578,698,1220,1245]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[578,698,1220,1245]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Adapantus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the tips of the male cerci which do not end in a spine, but are excavated (
<figureCitation box="[362,459,1256,1281]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Morphological details of Adapantus excavatus n. sp. A right male cercus, B male subgenital plate, C spinule at distal tip of hind femur. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600956/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 6 A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" box="[199,848,1292,1317]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1292,1317]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Description</emphasis>
(following the concept of 
<bibRefCitation author="Naskrecki, P." box="[635,836,1292,1317]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref14499" refString="Naskrecki, P. (2008 a) Sylvan Katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Pseudophyllinae) of the Guinean Forests of West Africa Hotspot: an overview and descriptions of new species. Zootaxa, 1712, 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="2008">Naskrecki, 2008a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" box="[199,751,1328,1353]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,298,1328,1353]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">General.</emphasis>
Body of medium size (habitus 
<figureCitation box="[649,742,1328,1353]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1046,1068]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1024]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1024]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Habitus. A Adapantus excavatus n. sp., B Conocephalus iris, var. guineensis, C Brachyamytta bombomensis n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600954/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 5 A</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,267,1364,1389]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Head.</emphasis>
Antennae more than twice as long as body; fastigium of vertex triangular, nearly reaching apex of antennal sockets (
<figureCitation box="[351,447,1400,1425]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Stridulatory organs of Adapantus (Adapantus) excavatus (A–D) and Adapantus (Neoadapantus) affluens (E–F; from Naskrecki, 2008a, reproduced with permission). A tegmina in situ, B stridulatory file, C, E left tegmen, from above, D, F right tegmen, from above. Scale C, D 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600958/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 7 A</figureCitation>
), grooved dorsally; frons flat. Scapus with small apical spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,287,1436,1461]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Thorax.</emphasis>
Humeral sinus of pronotum absent; lateral lobe wider than high; upper side of pronotum concave; anterior and posterior edge of prozona convexly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[867,981,1472,1497]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Stridulatory organs of Adapantus (Adapantus) excavatus (A–D) and Adapantus (Neoadapantus) affluens (E–F; from Naskrecki, 2008a, reproduced with permission). A tegmina in situ, B stridulatory file, C, E left tegmen, from above, D, F right tegmen, from above. Scale C, D 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600958/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 7 A</figureCitation>
); pronotum surface weakly granulate. Prosternum armed with two short spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,259,1546,1569]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Legs.</emphasis>
Genicular lobes of front and hind femur (
<figureCitation box="[745,842,1544,1569]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Morphological details of Adapantus excavatus n. sp. A right male cercus, B male subgenital plate, C spinule at distal tip of hind femur. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600956/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 6 C</figureCitation>
) armed with spines on both sides, mid femora with spines on inner side only; mid tibia dorsally unarmed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,275,1618,1641]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Wings.</emphasis>
Tegmina distinctly surpassing apex of abdomen; left stridulatory area coriaceous, with a large cell, shaped as mirror (
<figureCitation box="[357,455,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Stridulatory organs of Adapantus (Adapantus) excavatus (A–D) and Adapantus (Neoadapantus) affluens (E–F; from Naskrecki, 2008a, reproduced with permission). A tegmina in situ, B stridulatory file, C, E left tegmen, from above, D, F right tegmen, from above. Scale C, D 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600958/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 7 C</figureCitation>
); right stridulatory area with very large mirror (
<figureCitation box="[1002,1102,1652,1677]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Stridulatory organs of Adapantus (Adapantus) excavatus (A–D) and Adapantus (Neoadapantus) affluens (E–F; from Naskrecki, 2008a, reproduced with permission). A tegmina in situ, B stridulatory file, C, E left tegmen, from above, D, F right tegmen, from above. Scale C, D 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600958/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 7 D</figureCitation>
). Stridulatory vein very thick (
<figureCitation box="[159,288,1688,1713]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Stridulatory organs of Adapantus (Adapantus) excavatus (A–D) and Adapantus (Neoadapantus) affluens (E–F; from Naskrecki, 2008a, reproduced with permission). A tegmina in situ, B stridulatory file, C, E left tegmen, from above, D, F right tegmen, from above. Scale C, D 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600958/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 7 A, C</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file weakly bent, flat, with ca. 135 lamelliform teeth, 
<quantity box="[1044,1130,1689,1713]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[1202,1296,1688,1713]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionTargetBox="[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[159,1431,478,1916]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Stridulatory organs of Adapantus (Adapantus) excavatus (A–D) and Adapantus (Neoadapantus) affluens (E–F; from Naskrecki, 2008a, reproduced with permission). A tegmina in situ, B stridulatory file, C, E left tegmen, from above, D, F right tegmen, from above. Scale C, D 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600958/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 7 B</figureCitation>
). Hind wing as long as tegmina.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,312,1760,1785]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Cercus bent in apical third; apex of cercus slightly thickened, excavated (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1239,1760,1785]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Morphological details of Adapantus excavatus n. sp. A right male cercus, B male subgenital plate, C spinule at distal tip of hind femur. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600956/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 6 A</figureCitation>
); subgenital plate with small, triangular apical incision; stylus cylindrical, more than 3 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[1177,1271,1796,1821]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1755,1777]" captionTargetBox="[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[204,1382,589,1733]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Morphological details of Adapantus excavatus n. sp. A right male cercus, B male subgenital plate, C spinule at distal tip of hind femur. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600956/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 6 B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,329,1832,1857]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Coloration.</emphasis>
Coloration brown and green, sometimes mottled (
<figureCitation box="[925,1031,1832,1857]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1046,1068]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1024]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1024]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Habitus. A Adapantus excavatus n. sp., B Conocephalus iris, var. guineensis, C Brachyamytta bombomensis n. sp." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2600954/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Fig. 5 A</figureCitation>
); face light brown, without darker markings; hind wing fumose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" box="[199,1409,1904,1929]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis box="[199,361,1906,1929]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Measurements</emphasis>
(in mm). Body w/wings 32; body w/o wings: 29; pronotum: 5.5; tegmen: 25; hind femur: 18.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" box="[199,1325,1940,1965]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1940,1965]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet excavatus refers to the shape of the cercus (adjective, masculinum).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" box="[199,565,1976,2001]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,1976,2001]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
See below, part B.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1112,2037]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,536]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heller" authorityYear="2019" box="[199,341,2013,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excavatus">
<emphasis box="[199,341,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">A. excavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Krauss" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[494,675,2013,2037]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transmarinus">
<emphasis box="[494,675,2013,2037]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">A. transmarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the other species from 
<collectingCountry box="[952,1219,2012,2037]" name="Sao Tome and Principe" pageId="7" pageNumber="48">São Tomé and Príncipe</collectingCountry>
, not only in cercus shape, but also in the armature of the hind knees. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Krauss" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[702,882,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transmarinus">
<emphasis box="[702,882,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">A. transmarinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to a group of species without any spines, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heller" authorityYear="2019" box="[220,362,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excavatus">
<emphasis box="[220,362,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">A. excavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has spines as found in another species group. The new species differs in its stridulatory organs also distinctly from the three species of the genus described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Naskrecki, P." box="[863,1074,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref14499" refString="Naskrecki, P. (2008 a) Sylvan Katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Pseudophyllinae) of the Guinean Forests of West Africa Hotspot: an overview and descriptions of new species. Zootaxa, 1712, 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="2008">Naskrecki (2008a)</bibRefCitation>
. Comparing the other species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Karsch" authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1891" box="[273,470,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bardus">
<emphasis box="[273,382,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">A. bardus</emphasis>
Karsch
</taxonomicName>
(see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Naskrecki, P." box="[583,774,260,285]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref14499" refString="Naskrecki, P. (2008 a) Sylvan Katydids (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Pseudophyllinae) of the Guinean Forests of West Africa Hotspot: an overview and descriptions of new species. Zootaxa, 1712, 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="2008">Naskrecki 2008a</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authority="Bolivar" authorityName="Bolivar" box="[797,965,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="osorioi">
<emphasis box="[797,876,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">osorioi</emphasis>
Bolivar
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[980,1255,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heller" authorityYear="2019" box="[980,1093,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="excavatus">excavatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Krauss" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[1106,1255,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transmarinus">transmarinus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and some other species (according to photos in OSFO) have a very strong stridulatory vein and a more or less distinct mirror in the left tegmen, whereas Naskrecki’s three new species have a weak stridulatory vein and no indication of a left mirrorlike structure. The characters are clearly recognisable in Naskrecki’s excellent figure 8 and also mentioned in his text. 
<bibRefCitation author="Beier, M." box="[212,362,404,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" refId="ref11247" refString="Beier, M. (1962) Orthoptera Tettigoniidae (Pseudophyllinae I). Das Tierreich 73, Walter de Gruyter &amp; Co., Berlin, 468 pp." type="book" year="1962">Beier (1962)</bibRefCitation>
, however, mentions the presence of left and right mirrors as a characteristic of the genus 
<emphasis box="[151,278,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karsch" authorityYear="1891" box="[151,274,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Phaneropteridae" genus="Adapantus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Adapantus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The difference in the stridulatory organs is so distinctive that it may justify a subgeneric subdivision. The left mirror is an important predictor of a species’ carrier frequency (
<bibRefCitation author="Montealegre-Z, F. &amp; Ogden, J. &amp; Jonsson, T. &amp; Soulsbury, C. D." box="[998,1312,476,501]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" pagination="2068 - 2078" refId="ref14389" refString="Montealegre-Z, F., Ogden, J., Jonsson, T. &amp; Soulsbury, C. D. (2017) Morphological determinants of signal carrier frequency in katydids (Orthoptera): a comparative analysis using biophysical evidence of wing vibration. Journal of Evolutionary Biology, 30 (11), 2068 - 2078. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / jeb. 13179" type="journal article" year="2017">
Montealegre-Z 
<emphasis box="[1178,1230,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="49">et al</emphasis>
., 2017
</bibRefCitation>
) and large morphological differences may indicate differences in the communication system.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
